== Assessments That Can Wait

One of the most persistent myths about the golden hour is that you have to choose between bonding and necessary care. You do not. Almost everything hospitals consider "routine" can happen while your baby is on your chest.

=== APGAR Scoring on Your Chest

The APGAR score is a quick assessment performed at 1 minute and 5 minutes after birth #citation[8]. It evaluates appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration. Each is scored 0, 1, or 2.

Your baby does not need to leave your chest for this assessment. Your midwife or nurse can listen to the heart rate, observe breathing, check muscle tone, and note skin color while your baby remains in skin-to-skin contact.

=== Weighing and Measuring

Your baby's weight and length are almost never medically necessary in the first hour. These measurements are important for records, but they are informational, not urgent. They can easily wait until after the golden hour when your baby has stabilized and bonding has progressed.

=== Eye Ointment and Vitamin K

If you choose to proceed with eye ointment, timing requirements vary by state. Some states require application within the first hour. Even when it must be done during the golden hour, it can be applied while your baby is on your chest. See #link(<ch-eye-ointment>)[our Eye Ointment chapter] for more on eye prophylaxis.

If you choose to proceed with the vitamin K injection, it has more flexibility. The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends administration after the first feeding is completed but within six hours of birth #citation[9]. This means vitamin K can be delayed to allow for bonding and the first feeding during the golden hour. See #link(<ch-vitamin-k>)[our Vitamin K chapter] for more details on the vitamin K decision.

=== The First Bath

Bathing your newborn is not medically necessary in the first hours after birth. Current recommendations from the World Health Organization and American Academy of Pediatrics suggest delaying the first bath, ideally for at least 24 hours #citation[10].

Reasons to delay:
- Bathing causes temperature loss
- It disrupts bonding and breastfeeding
- Your baby is covered in vernix, a waxy substance that protects the skin and has antibacterial properties #citation[11]

Many parents now bathe their babies at home for the first time, when bonding is established and temperature regulation is more stable. See #link(<ch-first-bath>)[our First Bath chapter] for when to delay baby's first bath.

